# Feature Specification: Feature Update and Delete (CRUD Completion)

**Feature Branch**: `crud-feature`

**Created**: 2026-06-26

**Status**: Draft

**Input**: User description: "Add Update and Delete operations to features so the full CRUD lifecycle is supported in the Dev Team UI and API. Features can be renamed, reprioritized, and removed when no longer needed."

## Workspace Summary (Brownfield)

The Dev Team platform is an existing Go backend (`cmd/devteam`, `internal/api`, `internal/feature`, `internal/db`) with a React/TypeScript frontend (`ui/`). This feature extends the existing feature resource with the missing Update (U) and Delete (D) operations.

**Existing API surface** (discovered in `internal/api/server.go`):
- `GET /api/features` ‚Äî list (exists)
- `POST /api/features` ‚Äî create (exists)
- `GET /api/features/{id}` ‚Äî read single (exists)
- `POST /api/features/{id}/cancel` ‚Äî cancel (exists)
- `POST /api/features/{id}/recirculate` ‚Äî recirculate (exists)
- No `PUT`/`PATCH` for update, no `DELETE` for delete.

**Existing data layer** (`internal/db/feature_store.go`):
- `UpdateFeature(f FeatureRow)` already persists title/status/priority/worktree/phase/recirc_count ‚Äî title and priority are mutable today.
- `DeleteFeature(id)` already performs a hard `DELETE FROM features WHERE id = ?` (DB-level cascade via FK constraints handles related rows).
- `Feature` struct (`internal/feature/feature.go`): `ID`, `Title`, `Current` (Phase), `Status`, `Priority`, `IntakePath`, `SpecDir`, `WorktreeDir`, `CreatedAt`, `UpdatedAt`, `Dependencies`, `Repos`, `PhaseStates`.

**Existing status taxonomy** (`internal/feature/types.go`): `draft`, `in_progress`, `gate_blocked`, `passed`, `failed`, `done`, `recirculated`, `cancelled`, `waiting_for_feedback`. This spec MUST reuse these exact codes; no new statuses invented.

**Existing UI components**: `FeatureCard.tsx`, `FeatureList.tsx`, `IntakeForm.tsx`, `ProcessView.tsx`. Edit/delete affordances will be added to the feature detail view.

**Conventions to follow**: Go `net/http` mux with `mux.HandleFunc("METHOD /path", handler)` pattern; JSON request/response; SSE for live updates (`broadcastSSE`); tests via `httptest` and Playwright (`ui/e2e`).

## Constraint Register

| ID | Source | Section/Vector | Type | Constraint | Verification Method |
|----|--------|----------------|------|------------|---------------------|
| CON-001 | Existing API | server.go:162-192 | consistency | Use the existing `mux.HandleFunc("METHOD /path", handler)` route registration pattern | Inspection of new routes in server.go |
| CON-002 | Existing data layer | feature_store.go:101-111 | consistency | Reuse `UpdateFeature(FeatureRow)`; do not introduce a parallel update path | Unit test calling UpdateFeature directly |
| CON-003 | Existing data layer | feature_store.go:178-185 | consistency | Reuse `DeleteFeature(id)` for hard delete; do not add a soft-delete column | Integration test verifying row removal |
| CON-004 | Status taxonomy | types.go:54-64 | consistency | Use ONLY the existing `Status*` constants; no new statuses introduced | Grep new code for any string literal status not in the const block |
| CON-005 | Overconfidence prevention | error paths | correctness | Every error path returns a structured JSON error with an HTTP status from {400, 404, 409} | Negative ACs below |
| CON-006 | Empty-state rule | core-workflow ¬ßConstruction | correctness | `GET /api/features` returns `200 []` (never `null`, never `404`) when no features exist | Empty-state AC |
| CON-007 | Agent failure mode | core-workflow ¬ßConstruction | correctness | JSON arrays in responses are `[]` not `null` | Response-body assertion |
| CON-008 | Existing Cancel | feature.go:193-197 | consistency | `Cancel()` already sets `StatusCancelled`; delete is a separate operation, not a status change | Verify delete removes the row, cancel keeps it |
| CON-009 | ID immutability | feature.go:77-98 | correctness | Feature ID is generated at intake and MUST NOT change on edit | AC-EDIT-ID-IMMUTABLE |
| CON-010 | Phase-state safety | feature.go:113-148 | correctness | Editing a feature that is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback` MUST be rejected to avoid racing the pipeline | AC-EDIT-BUSY |

## User Scenarios & Testing *(mandatory)*

### User Story 1 - Rename and Reprioritize a Feature (Priority: P1)

A user views a feature's detail page and edits its title and priority. The system validates the input, rejects edits while the feature is mid-pipeline, and persists the change. The updated title/priority appear in the feature list and detail view.

**Why this priority**: Update is the missing "U" in CRUD. Without it, users cannot correct a typo in a title or fix a wrong priority without canceling and recreating the feature (losing all pipeline state). This is the core gap.

**Independent Test**: Create a draft feature, `PATCH /api/features/{id}` with `{"title":"new name","priority":2}`, then `GET /api/features/{id}` and verify the response shows the new title and priority. No other story needed for this to deliver value.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** a feature with `status: draft`, **When** a user sends `PATCH /api/features/{id}` with `{"title":"Renamed Feature","priority":2}`, **Then** the response is `200` with the updated feature JSON (new title, priority 2, same id, `updated_at` advanced)
2. **Given** a feature with `status: in_progress`, **When** a user sends `PATCH /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `409 Conflict` with a JSON error body explaining the feature is being processed and edits are disabled
3. **Given** a feature with `status: waiting_for_feedback`, **When** a user sends `PATCH /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `409 Conflict` (busy state, edits disabled)
4. **Given** a feature that does not exist, **When** a user sends `PATCH /api/features/missing-id`, **Then** the response is `404 Not Found`
5. **Given** a valid feature id, **When** a user sends `PATCH` with an empty title or title > 200 chars, **Then** the response is `400 Bad Request`
6. **Given** a valid feature id, **When** a user sends `PATCH` with `priority` not in {1,2,3}, **Then** the response is `400 Bad Request`
7. **Given** a successful edit, **When** the feature list is next loaded, **Then** the edited title/priority are reflected and an SSE event `feature_updated` is broadcast

### User Story 2 - Delete a Feature (Priority: P1)

A user removes a feature that is draft or in a terminal state (done/cancelled). The system hard-deletes the row and all related data (artifacts, phase states, sessions, notes, questions, events), broadcasts an SSE event, and the feature disappears from the list. In-progress features cannot be deleted directly ‚Äî they must be cancelled first.

**Why this priority**: Delete is the missing "D" in CRUD. Users accumulate abandoned drafts and completed features; without delete, the list grows unbounded. Pairs with Update to complete CRUD.

**Independent Test**: Create a draft feature, `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, then `GET /api/features/{id}` and verify `404`, and `GET /api/features` no longer lists it.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** a feature with `status: draft`, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `204 No Content` and a subsequent `GET /api/features/{id}` returns `404`
2. **Given** a feature with `status: done`, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `204 No Content` (terminal features are deletable)
3. **Given** a feature with `status: cancelled`, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `204 No Content` (terminal features are deletable)
4. **Given** a feature with `status: in_progress`, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `409 Conflict` with a JSON error explaining the feature must be cancelled before deletion
5. **Given** a feature with `status: waiting_for_feedback`, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/{id}`, **Then** the response is `409 Conflict` (cancel first)
6. **Given** a feature that does not exist, **When** a user sends `DELETE /api/features/missing-id`, **Then** the response is `404 Not Found`
7. **Given** a successful delete, **When** the feature list is next loaded, **Then** the deleted feature is absent and an SSE event `feature_deleted` is broadcast
8. **Given** a deleted feature, **When** a later query checks related tables (phase_states, notes, questions, events, sessions for that feature_id), **Then** no rows remain (cascade verified)

### User Story 3 - Update and Delete Affordances in the UI (Priority: P2)

From the feature detail page, the user can open an edit form (title + priority) and a delete action behind a confirm dialog. Both are gated by the same status rules as the API. List-card quick edit is out of scope for this iteration.

**Why this priority**: The API support (US-1, US-2) is the substance; the UI is the user-facing surface. P2 because the API delivers value even with curl, but the UI is what makes it a product.

**Independent Test**: Open a draft feature's detail page, click "Edit", change the title, save, and verify the detail page and list reflect the new title. Then click "Delete", confirm, and verify the feature is gone from the list.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** a draft feature's detail page is open, **When** the user clicks "Edit" and submits a new title and priority, **Then** the detail page shows the updated values without a full reload
2. **Given** a feature in `in_progress` on the detail page, **When** the user views it, **Then** the "Edit" affordance is disabled or hidden with a tooltip explaining why
3. **Given** a draft feature's detail page, **When** the user clicks "Delete", **Then** a confirm dialog appears; confirming it removes the feature and navigates back to the list
4. **Given** a feature in `in_progress` on the detail page, **When** the user views it, **Then** the "Delete" affordance is disabled or hidden with a tooltip ("Cancel the feature first")
5. **Given** a delete is confirmed, **When** the list view is shown, **Then** the deleted feature is no longer present
6. **Given** an edit or delete API call fails (network/409), **When** the UI receives the error, **Then** a toast or inline message shows the error text from the response body

### Edge Cases

- **Empty feature store**: `GET /api/features` after deleting the last feature returns `200 []` (not `null`, not `404`). Verified by CON-006/CON-007.
- **Delete a feature with active tmux session**: `status: in_progress` is rejected by the 409 rule; the user must cancel first, which stops the session. No orphaned tmux session from a delete.
- **Concurrent edit and phase advance**: If a phase advance lands between an edit request and its persistence, the edit is rejected because the status check happens at handler entry and the `UpdateFeature` is a single statement. [ASSUMPTION: no row-level locking needed for MVP ‚Äî the 409-on-busy rule removes the common race. A DB transaction around status-check-then-update is the upgrade path if drift is observed.]
- **Edit to identical values**: Allowed, returns `200` with `updated_at` advanced. No "no-op" short-circuit; keeps the contract simple.
- **Delete then recreate same id**: IDs are slug-derived and creation assigns a unique id; recreating a deleted id is permitted since the row is gone. [ASSUMPTION: id collisions after delete are the user's problem; the create path already enforces uniqueness.]
- **PATCH with unknown fields**: Unknown fields in the request body are ignored (no mass-assignment). Only `title` and `priority` are read.
- **PATCH with no body**: `400 Bad Request`.
- **DELETE on a feature with prepared impl worktrees**: The worktree directory is left on disk (delete does not `rm -rf` worktrees). [ASSUMPTION: worktree cleanup is a separate ops concern; deleting the DB row is the feature's scope. Documented for the Architect.]
- **Status `gate_blocked`, `passed`, `failed`, `recirculated`**: These are mid-pipeline states. Edits and deletes are rejected with `409` for all non-{draft, done, cancelled} states. The rule is: only `draft` and terminal (`done`, `cancelled`) are editable/deletable.

## Requirements *(mandatory)*

### Functional Requirements

- **FR-001**: System MUST expose `PATCH /api/features/{id}` to update a feature's `title` and `priority`. Source: US-001
- **FR-002**: System MUST expose `DELETE /api/features/{id}` to remove a feature and cascade-delete all related data. Source: US-002
- **FR-003**: System MUST reject `PATCH` with `409 Conflict` when the feature's status is not in {`draft`, `done`, `cancelled`}. Source: US-001, CON-010
- **FR-004**: System MUST reject `DELETE` with `409 Conflict` when the feature's status is not in {`draft`, `done`, `cancelled`}. Source: US-002, CON-010
- **FR-005**: System MUST reject `PATCH` with `400 Bad Request` when `title` is empty or longer than 200 characters. Source: US-001
- **FR-006**: System MUST reject `PATCH` with `400 Bad Request` when `priority` is not 1, 2, or 3. Source: US-001
- **FR-007**: System MUST return `404 Not Found` for `PATCH` or `DELETE` on a non-existent feature id. Source: US-001, US-002
- **FR-008**: System MUST return `204 No Content` with an empty body for a successful `DELETE`. Source: US-002
- **FR-009**: System MUST NOT change the feature `id` on any edit. Source: US-001, CON-009
- **FR-010**: System MUST reuse the existing `UpdateFeature(FeatureRow)` and `DeleteFeature(id)` data-layer functions. Source: CON-002, CON-003
- **FR-011**: System MUST broadcast an SSE event `feature_updated` on a successful `PATCH` and `feature_deleted` on a successful `DELETE`. Source: US-001, US-002
- **FR-012**: System MUST ignore unknown fields in the `PATCH` request body (no mass-assignment of `id`, `status`, `current_phase`, `intake_path`, `spec_dir`, `worktree_dir`, `created_at`). Source: US-001
- **FR-013**: UI MUST provide an edit form on the feature detail page gated by the same status rules as the API. Source: US-003
- **FR-014**: UI MUST provide a delete action on the feature detail page behind a confirm dialog, gated by the same status rules as the API. Source: US-003
- **FR-015**: UI MUST disable or hide edit/delete affordances for non-editable states with an explanatory tooltip. Source: US-003
- **FR-016**: System MUST return `200 []` (not `null`, not `404`) for `GET /api/features` when no features exist, including after a delete empties the store. Source: CON-006, CON-007
- **FR-017**: System MUST return JSON error bodies with an `error` field for all `400`/`404`/`409` responses on the new endpoints. Source: CON-005

### Key Entities and Relationships

**Entity: Feature** (existing, extended)
- Attributes: `id` (immutable), `title` (mutable, 1-200 chars), `priority` (mutable, 1-3), `current_phase` (system-controlled), `status` (system-controlled), `intake_path` (immutable), `spec_dir` (immutable), `worktree_dir` (system-controlled), `created_at` (immutable), `updated_at` (auto-advanced on edit), `dependencies` (immutable via this API), `repos` (immutable via this API), `phase_states` (system-controlled).
- Editable subset: `{title, priority}` only.
- Relationships: 1 Feature ‚Üí many PhaseStates, Notes, Questions, Events, Sessions, Recirculations, Artifacts. Delete cascades to all.

**State transitions for editability/deletability** (not the feature's lifecycle, which already exists):
- `draft` ‚Üí editable, deletable
- `in_progress` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable (must cancel first)
- `gate_blocked` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable
- `passed` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable
- `failed` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable
- `recirculated` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable
- `waiting_for_feedback` ‚Üí not editable, not deletable
- `done` ‚Üí editable, deletable (terminal)
- `cancelled` ‚Üí editable, deletable (terminal)

Invalid operations: any edit/delete on a non-{draft, done, cancelled} feature returns `409`.

## Success Criteria *(mandatory)*

- **SC-001**: A user can rename a draft feature and see the new name in the list and detail view within one page reload (or immediately via SSE). Measured by: `PATCH` returns 200, subsequent `GET` returns the new title.
- **SC-002**: A user can change a feature's priority between P1/P2/P3 and the change persists across reloads. Measured by: `PATCH` with priority N, then `GET` returns priority N.
- **SC-003**: A user can delete a draft or terminal feature and it no longer appears in `GET /api/features`. Measured by: `DELETE` returns 204, `GET /api/features/{id}` returns 404, the feature is absent from the list.
- **SC-004**: All related data for a deleted feature is removed. Measured by: zero rows in `phase_states`, `notes`, `questions`, `events`, `sessions`, `recirculations` for the deleted feature_id.
- **SC-005**: Edit/delete attempts on a mid-pipeline feature are rejected with `409`. Measured by: a `409` response with a JSON error body for each of {in_progress, waiting_for_feedback, gate_blocked, passed, failed, recirculated}.
- **SC-006**: The feature list endpoint returns `200 []` after the last feature is deleted. Measured by: response body is exactly `[]`.
- **SC-007**: The UI shows edit/delete affordances only on editable/deletable features. Measured by: Playwright E2E asserting the edit/delete controls are present for a draft feature and absent/disabled for an in-progress feature.

## Assumptions *(mandatory)*

- [ASSUMPTION: Editable fields are limited to `title` and `priority`. `intake_path`, `spec_dir`, `repos`, `dependencies` are set at intake and not user-editable after creation.]
- [ASSUMPTION: Delete is a hard delete (row + cascade). The existing `DeleteFeature` DB function already does this; no soft-delete or `deleted` status is introduced. Cancel is the existing soft-state operation and remains separate.]
- [ASSUMPTION: Edit and delete are allowed only when `status` is `draft`, `done`, or `cancelled`. Mid-pipeline features must be cancelled first. This is the conservative default to avoid racing the pipeline.]
- [ASSUMPTION: Edit is available only from the feature detail page, not inline on the list card. Inline quick-edit is out of scope for this iteration.]
- [ASSUMPTION: The feature `id` is immutable. It is never regenerated from a new title on rename.]
- [ASSUMPTION: No row-level DB locking is required for MVP. The 409-on-busy rule removes the common race; a transaction around status-check-then-update is the upgrade path if drift is observed.]
- [ASSUMPTION: Deleting a feature does not `rm -rf` its spec worktree on disk. Worktree cleanup is an ops concern outside this feature's scope. The Architect may add a task if needed.]
- [ASSUMPTION: No authentication/authorization is introduced by this feature. The platform is currently single-user/local; RBAC is out of scope. The security extension's threat model is acknowledged but deferred ‚Äî see Security Notes.]
- [ASSUMPTION: Unknown fields in a `PATCH` body are silently ignored (no mass-assignment), consistent with JSON decode-into-struct semantics in Go.]
- [ASSUMPTION: `GET /api/features` after deleting the last feature returns `200 []` ‚Äî this is an existing behavior, re-asserted here so a delete-induced regression is caught.]

## Security Notes

The security extension is loaded for P1 features. This feature handles user input (title) and destructive actions (delete). Threat-model assessment:

- **Spoofing**: N/A in current single-user model; deferred (see ASSUMPTION above).
- **Tampering**: The 409-on-busy rule and immutable-id rule prevent tampering with a feature mid-pipeline. Mass-assignment is blocked by decoding only `{title, priority}`.
- **Repudiation**: Delete broadcasts an SSE event and (by convention) the event log records it. Existing event logging is assumed sufficient for MVP.
- **Information disclosure**: Error bodies must not leak internal paths or stack traces. The spec requires a structured `error` field only.
- **Denial of service**: No rate limiting introduced by this feature. [ASSUMPTION: the platform is local/single-user; rate limiting is deferred.]
- **Elevation of privilege**: N/A in current model.

Data classification: `title` and `priority` are public (already exposed via `GET /api/features`). No new confidential fields introduced. The `id` is internal but already public via the API. No restricted fields are exposed by the new endpoints.

## Constitution Compliance

No `constitution.md` exists in the repo root or `.specify/`. N/A.
