Dev Team is a Go backend (`cmd/devteam/`, `internal/`) with a React/TypeScript frontend (`ui/`). The platform dispatches `opencode` agents to work on features in per-spec git worktrees via tmux sessions.

**Current provider selection**: There is no provider/model configuration today. Each dispatched opencode agent inherits whatever model opencode selects by default (driven by the agent's own config / the operator's global opencode setup). The dispatch path is:

- `internal/role/dispatcher.go` + `internal/role/tmux.go` ‚Äî build a temp `OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR`, write `CONTEXT.md` + `agents/<role>.md`, then `exec opencode run --dangerously-skip-permissions --agent <role>`.
- `internal/config/config.go` ‚Äî `Config` struct loaded from `devteam.yaml`. No provider/model fields today.
- `devteam.yaml` ‚Äî pipeline config; has no `providers:` section.

**Conventions to follow**:
- Config lives in `devteam.yaml`, parsed by `internal/config/config.go` (YAML, `gopkg.in/yaml.v3`).
- Dispatch injects env vars via tmux `-e` flags and writes an `opencode.json` into the temp context dir.
- Go tests use `httptest` / table-driven patterns; `go test ./... -count=1 -timeout 120s`.
- AGENTS.md rule: phase instructions must stay platform-agnostic (no hardcoded build/test commands).

## Source Discovery

This feature does not implement an external protocol or RFC. The governing sources are:

1. **opencode configuration model**: opencode agents read config from `OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR` (an `opencode.json`) and select a model from that config. Dev Team already writes this config dir per dispatch. The feature adds provider/model fields to that generated config.
2. **OpenAI-compatible API convention**: the catch-all provider type targets any endpoint that accepts an OpenAI-style `base_url` override and `Authorization: Bearer <key>`. No RFC; convention only.
3. **Internal conventions**: `AGENTS.md`, `devteam.yaml` schema, `internal/config/config.go`, `internal/role/{dispatcher,tmux}.go`. No `CONTRIBUTING.md`.

No external test vectors or conformance suites apply. No standard-defined error taxonomy ‚Äî error codes are Dev Team's own (see Error Scenarios).

## Constraint Register

| ID | Source | Section/Vector | Type | Constraint | Verification Method |
|----|--------|----------------|------|------------|---------------------|
| CON-001 | AGENTS.md | Platform-agnostic rule | consistency | Phase instructions/config must not hardcode provider-specific commands; provider config is data in `devteam.yaml`, not code paths per provider | Config schema review |
| CON-002 | opencode config | OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR | correctness | Dispatched agent's `opencode.json` must declare the chosen provider/model so opencode uses it | Inspect generated `opencode.json` in temp context dir during dispatch |
| CON-003 | OpenAI-compatible convention | base_url + Bearer | correctness | A "openai-compatible" provider is fully described by `base_url` + `api_key_env` + `model`; no provider-specific code branches | Unit test: any base_url+model dispatches identically |
| CON-004 | Answer Q5 | credentials | security | API keys are NEVER stored in `devteam.yaml` or the DB; only the env var *name* is stored; the key is read from the operator's environment at dispatch time | Config parse test: yaml contains no literal key values; dispatch test: key passed via env, not config file |
| CON-005 | Answer Q6 | failure | resiliency | Provider unavailable / auth error mid-pipeline = fail the dispatch immediately and surface the error to the operator; no silent retry or fallback | Error path test: dispatch returns failure result with provider error in `result.Error` |
| CON-006 | Answer Q2 | granularity | correctness | Provider/model granularity = per role (pm, architect, developer, reviewer, tester, ops). Phases inherit the role's provider. | Config schema: `providers:` defines providers; `roles:` (or per-role provider key) maps role‚Üíprovider+model |
| CON-007 | Answer Q1 | scope | correctness | Feature makes the currently-hardcoded model configurable per role via `devteam.yaml`; it does not add a Dev Team‚ÜíLLM direct API call path (Dev Team still dispatches opencode) | Architecture review: no new HTTP client to LLM providers in Dev Team itself |
| CON-008 | Answer Q7 | UI | scope | Web UI shows NO provider info; configuration is operator-only via `devteam.yaml` | UI review: no provider fields/routes added |
| CON-009 | Answer Q8 | model discovery | scope | Dev Team does NOT query provider APIs to list/validate models; model ID is a free-form string the operator types | Config schema: `model` is a plain string; no model-listing code path |
| CON-010 | Backward compat | absent config | resiliency | When `providers:` is absent or a role has no provider mapping, Dev Team falls back to opencode's default model (current behavior) so existing deployments keep working | Dispatch test: no providers config ‚Üí generated opencode.json has no model override |

## User Scenarios & Testing

### User Story 1 - Operator configures a provider and assigns it per role (Priority: P1)

An operator adds a `providers:` section to `devteam.yaml` defining one or more OpenAI-compatible providers (each with a name, `base_url`, `api_key_env`, and optionally a default `model`). The operator then maps each Dev Team role (pm, architect, developer, reviewer, tester, ops) to a provider + model. On the next dispatch, the agent for that role runs against the configured provider/model instead of opencode's default.

**Why this priority**: This is the core of the feature ‚Äî without per-role provider config, nothing else matters. It is independently testable: a single provider + one role mapping is a viable MVP.

**Independent Test**: Configure one provider in `devteam.yaml`, map the `pm` role to it, run a dispatch, and verify the generated `opencode.json` in the temp context dir declares that provider/model.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** `devteam.yaml` has a `providers:` section with one provider and `roles.pm` references it, **When** Dev Team dispatches the pm agent, **Then** the dispatched opencode process receives an `opencode.json` that sets the provider's `base_url` and the role's `model`, and the provider's API key is injected from the named env var.
2. **Given** `devteam.yaml` defines two providers `anthropic` and `local`, **When** `roles.developer` maps to `local` and `roles.pm` maps to `anthropic`, **Then** a developer dispatch uses `local` and a pm dispatch uses `anthropic`.
3. **Given** `devteam.yaml` has no `providers:` section, **When** any role is dispatched, **Then** no model override is written and opencode's default behavior is preserved.

---

### User Story 2 - Operator supplies API credentials via environment variables (Priority: P1)

The operator sets the API key in their shell environment under the variable name declared in the provider's `api_key_env`. Dev Team reads only the *name* of the variable from `devteam.yaml` and passes the key's *value* into the dispatched agent's environment. No API key is ever written to `devteam.yaml`, the database, or logs.

**Why this priority**: Credentials are security-critical and tightly coupled to US-1 ‚Äî a provider config without a key is unusable. Independently testable by dispatching with/without the env var set.

**Independent Test**: Declare a provider with `api_key_env: MY_KEY`, set `MY_KEY=secret` in the environment, dispatch, and verify `MY_KEY=secret` is present in the agent process env while `devteam.yaml` contains only the literal string `MY_KEY`.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** a provider with `api_key_env: OPENAI_API_KEY` and the operator's environment has `OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...`, **When** Dev Team dispatches an agent using that provider, **Then** the agent process environment contains `OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...` and `devteam.yaml` contains no key value.
2. **Given** a provider with `api_key_env: OPENAI_API_KEY` and the env var is unset, **When** Dev Team dispatches, **Then** the dispatch fails fast with a clear operator-facing error naming the missing variable (per CON-005).

---

### User Story 3 - Dispatch fails fast on provider/auth errors (Priority: P2)

When the selected provider is unreachable, returns an auth error, or the API key env var is missing, Dev Team fails the dispatch immediately, records the error in the dispatch result, and surfaces it to the operator. There is no automatic fallback to a secondary provider and no silent retry loop.

**Why this priority**: Failure handling is important but not required for the happy-path MVP. It is independently testable by pointing a provider at a bad `base_url` or omitting the key.

**Independent Test**: Configure a provider with `base_url: http://127.0.0.1:1` (unreachable), dispatch, and verify the dispatch result has `Success=false` and an error message referencing the provider.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** a provider whose `base_url` is unreachable, **When** an agent is dispatched against it, **Then** the `DispatchResult.Success` is `false` and `DispatchResult.Error` contains a message identifying the provider failure.
2. **Given** a provider whose API key env var is missing, **When** Dev Team prepares the dispatch, **Then** the dispatch is aborted before spawning opencode with an error naming the missing env var.
3. **Given** a dispatch that fails with a provider/auth error, **Then** no retry attempt is made and no secondary provider is selected.

---

### User Story 4 - Backward-compatible default when no provider is configured (Priority: P2)

Existing deployments that do not add a `providers:` section continue to work exactly as today: Dev Team writes no model override into the generated `opencode.json`, and opencode selects its default model. No migration, no required config changes.

**Why this priority**: Protects existing users from a breaking change. Independently testable by dispatching with an empty `devteam.yaml`.

**Independent Test**: Load a `devteam.yaml` with no `providers:` key, dispatch any role, and verify the generated `opencode.json` has no `model`/provider fields and the dispatch succeeds.

**Acceptance Scenarios**:

1. **Given** `devteam.yaml` has no `providers:` section, **When** any role is dispatched, **Then** the generated `opencode.json` contains no provider/model override and the dispatch succeeds.
2. **Given** `devteam.yaml` has `providers:` defined but a given role has no mapping, **When** that role is dispatched, **Then** no override is written for that role and opencode's default applies.

---

### Edge Cases

- **Empty `providers:` map**: `providers:` exists but is empty ‚Üí treat as "no providers configured" (US-4 fallback), not an error.
- **Role mapped to a provider name that doesn't exist**: e.g. `roles.developer: {provider: ghost}` where `ghost` is not in `providers:` ‚Üí fail the dispatch with a clear config error naming the missing provider.
- **Provider `base_url` empty or malformed**: fail dispatch with a config validation error; do not spawn opencode against an empty URL.
- **`api_key_env` names a variable that is set but empty**: treat as missing (fail fast) ‚Äî an empty key will not authenticate.
- **Two providers with the same name**: config load fails with a duplicate-provider error.
- **`model` field empty for a role mapping**: fall back to the provider's default `model`; if the provider has no default either, fail with a config error.
- **All six roles mapped to the same provider**: valid; no artificial uniqueness constraint.
- **Operator changes `devteam.yaml` while a dispatch is running**: the running dispatch keeps its already-generated config; the next dispatch picks up the new config (no hot-reload required for v1).

## Requirements

### Functional Requirements

- **FR-001** (Source: US-1, CON-006): The system SHALL parse a `providers:` section from `devteam.yaml` where each provider has: `name`, `base_url`, `api_key_env`, and an optional default `model`.
- **FR-002** (Source: US-1, CON-006): The system SHALL allow each Dev Team role (pm, architect, developer, reviewer, tester, ops) to be mapped to a provider + model, overriding the provider's default model.
- **FR-003** (Source: US-1, CON-002): At dispatch time, the system SHALL write the selected provider's `base_url` and the role's `model` into the generated `opencode.json` in the temp `OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR` so opencode uses them.
- **FR-004** (Source: US-2, CON-004): The system SHALL resolve the API key by reading the environment variable named in `api_key_env` and inject its value into the dispatched agent's environment. The system MUST NOT write the key value into `devteam.yaml`, the database, or log output.
- **FR-005** (Source: US-3, CON-005): When the configured provider is unreachable, returns an auth error, or the named env var is missing/empty, the system SHALL fail the dispatch immediately with `Success=false` and a descriptive `Error`, and MUST NOT retry or fall back to another provider.
- **FR-006** (Source: US-4, CON-010): When `providers:` is absent, empty, or a role has no mapping, the system SHALL write no model override into `opencode.json` and dispatch using opencode's default behavior.
- **FR-007** (Source: US-1): The system SHALL validate provider config at load time and reject: duplicate provider names, a `base_url` that is empty, and a role mapping that references an undefined provider name.
- **FR-008** (Source: CON-003): A provider SHALL be fully described by `name`, `base_url`, `api_key_env`, and `model` (default or per-role). There MUST be no provider-specific code branches (no `if provider == "anthropic"`).
- **FR-009** (Source: CON-008, CON-009): The web UI SHALL NOT display provider/model information, and the system SHALL NOT query provider APIs to list or validate models. The `model` field is a free-form operator-supplied string.
- **FR-010** (Source: CON-007): The system SHALL continue to dispatch agents via opencode; it MUST NOT add a direct Dev Team ‚Üí LLM HTTP client path.

### Key Entities

- **Provider**: `name` (unique identifier), `base_url` (OpenAI-compatible endpoint), `api_key_env` (name of env var holding the key ‚Äî never the key itself), `model` (optional default model string). Relationships: referenced by zero or more role mappings.
- **RoleProviderMapping**: maps a Dev Team role ‚Üí `{provider: <name>, model: <optional string>}`. If `model` is omitted, the provider's default `model` is used. Relationships: each mapping references exactly one Provider.
- **DispatchConfig** (derived, not stored): the resolved `{base_url, model, api_key_value}` computed at dispatch time from Provider + RoleProviderMapping + environment. Lives only for the duration of one dispatch; written into the temp `opencode.json` + agent env.

## Success Criteria

- **SC-001**: An operator can configure two different providers and map two different roles to them, dispatch both roles, and verify (by inspecting the generated `opencode.json` and the agent env) that each dispatch used its assigned provider/model.
- **SC-002**: An existing `devteam.yaml` with no `providers:` section dispatches all roles successfully with no change to generated `opencode.json` content versus the pre-feature behavior.
- **SC-003**: No API key value appears in `devteam.yaml`, the Dev Team database, or any log line emitted during a successful dispatch.
- **SC-004**: A dispatch against a provider with a missing `api_key_env` value or an unreachable `base_url` fails within the dispatch step (no opencode process is spawned for the missing-key case; the spawned process's failure is captured for the unreachable case) and the error is visible to the operator.
- **SC-005**: The implementation contains zero provider-specific code branches (no string comparisons against provider names); all provider behavior is data-driven from the `providers:` config.

## Assumptions

- [ASSUMPTION: opencode reads the model/provider from the `opencode.json` in `OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR`.] Dev Team already writes this dir per dispatch; the feature adds fields to that file. (To be confirmed by the Architect against the opencode config schema.)
- [ASSUMPTION: "OpenAI-compatible" means an endpoint that accepts OpenAI-style `base_url` override + `Authorization: Bearer <key>`.] No RFC governs this; it is the prevailing convention. Provider-specific auth schemes (e.g. Anthropic's native header) are out of scope for v1 ‚Äî operators point at an OpenAI-compatible gateway/proxy if they need a native provider.
- [ASSUMPTION: The operator restarts Dev Team after editing `devteam.yaml`.] No hot-reload of provider config is required for v1.
- [ASSUMPTION: Per-role granularity is sufficient; phases inherit the dispatched role's provider.] Per-phase override is out of scope (Answer Q2 chose per-role).
- [ASSUMPTION: API keys live in the operator's process environment, not in the DB or a secrets file.] The Dev Team service process must have the relevant env vars set at launch.
- [ASSUMPTION: Model IDs are free-form strings; validation is the operator's responsibility.] Dev Team does not call the provider to verify a model exists (Answer Q8).

## Out of Scope

- Web UI for viewing/editing provider config (Answer Q7).
- Model catalog discovery / validation (Answer Q8).
- Per-phase provider granularity (Answer Q2 ‚Äî per-role only).
- Automatic fallback to a secondary provider on failure (Answer Q6 ‚Äî fail fast).
- Direct Dev Team ‚Üí LLM API calls bypassing opencode (Answer Q1).
- Hot-reload of `devteam.yaml` without restart.
- Provider-specific auth schemes beyond OpenAI-compatible `Bearer` token.

## Constitution Compliance

Constitution at `.specify/memory/constitution.md` (v1.1, ratified 2026-06-19). Principles checked:

| Principle | Status | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| I. Spec-Driven, Always | Compliant | Feature starts with this spec; no implementation before spec.md + acceptance.md + repos.yaml. |
| II. Six Roles, Fixed Pipeline | Compliant | No role reorder/skip. Provider config touches dispatcher (construction-era) only; PM defines, Architect plans, Developer implements, Reviewer/Tester verify. |
| III. Central Spec, Distributed Implementation | Compliant | Single spec in spec repo; repos.yaml declares scope (devteam primary). No spec duplication. |
| IV. Two Intake Paths, One Output Format | Compliant | Loose idea intake ‚Üí spec.md + acceptance.md + repos.yaml, same artifact shape as any feature. |
| V. Proof-of-Work Gates | Compliant | acceptance.md AC-001..AC-022 each Given/When/Then with test level + verification; downstream roles must quote evidence. |
| VI. Cross-Repo Coherence | Compliant (single-repo) | Feature spans one repo (devteam); no cross-repo coordination needed. |
| VII. Self-Bootstrap | Compliant | Feature improves the platform's own dispatch; no external dependency. |
| VIII. Go, Minimal Dependencies | Compliant | Config parsing reuses existing `internal/config/config.go` + `gopkg.in/yaml.v3`; no new runtime dependency, no Python. |
| IX. Pipeline Governance | Compliant | Phase-appropriate rules govern each role; security/resiliency extensions load for P1 (this feature is P1). |
| X. Learn From Cistern | Compliant | Provider config is structured data in `devteam.yaml`, not code paths per provider (CON-001, CON-003); role identity stays role-centric. |

## Error Scenarios

| User Action | Success | Error Condition | Expected Response |
|---|---|---|---|
| Load `devteam.yaml` with providers | Config parsed | Duplicate provider name | Config load error: "duplicate provider name: X" (fail at startup, not dispatch) |
| Load `devteam.yaml` with providers | Config parsed | Role maps to undefined provider | Config load error: "role 'developer' references unknown provider 'ghost'" |
| Load `devteam.yaml` with providers | Config parsed | Provider `base_url` empty | Config load error: "provider 'X' has empty base_url" |
| Dispatch role with mapped provider | Agent runs with provider | `api_key_env` variable unset/empty | Dispatch fails fast: `Success=false`, `Error="provider 'X': api key env var 'OPENAI_API_KEY' is not set"`, no opencode spawned |
| Dispatch role with mapped provider | Agent runs with provider | `base_url` unreachable / returns auth error | `DispatchResult.Success=false`, `Error` contains provider failure detail; no retry, no fallback |
| Dispatch role with no mapping | Agent runs with opencode default | n/a | Success (fallback path) |
| Dispatch role with mapped provider | Agent runs with provider | `model` empty and provider has no default model | Config load error: "role 'pm' has no model and provider 'X' has no default model" |

## Empty State Behavior

- No `providers:` section ‚Üí US-4 fallback; no override written; not an error.
- `providers:` present but empty map ‚Üí same as absent (fallback).
- A role with no mapping ‚Üí same as absent (fallback for that role only).

## State Transitions

This feature adds no persistent state machine. `Provider` and `RoleProviderMapping` are config-loaded (not DB-stored) and exist only as in-memory config after `devteam.yaml` is parsed. The only lifecycle is: config load ‚Üí (validated) ‚Üí used at dispatch time.
