## Workspace Summary (Brownfield)
## User Scenarios & Testing
### User Story 1 - Edit a Feature's Title and Priority (Priority: P1)
### User Story 2 - Delete a Feature (Priority: P1)
### User Story 3 - List Reflects Edits and Deletions (Priority: P2)
**Why this priority**: Pure consistency follow-on. The list already exists; this story ensures the new mutations propagate to the existing list view. Not independently shippable as an MVP (depends on US-1/US-2), but trivially verifiable.
### Edge Cases
## Requirements
### Functional Requirements
- **FR-001**: The system SHALL expose `PATCH /api/features/{id}` to update a feature's editable fields (title, priority). Source: US-1.
- **FR-002**: The system SHALL reject PATCH with `409 Conflict` (`feature_in_progress`) when the feature status is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`. Source: US-1, human answer "no edits while processing".
- **FR-003**: The system SHALL validate the title on PATCH: non-empty after trim, ‚â§200 chars, returning `400` with code `empty_title` or `title_too_long` respectively. Source: US-1 (mirrors `createFeature` validation).
- **FR-004**: The system SHALL validate priority on PATCH: if present, must be 1‚Äì3, returning `400` with code `invalid_priority`; if absent, priority is left unchanged (partial update). Source: US-1.
- **FR-005**: The system SHALL return `404 Not Found` (`feature_not_found`) for PATCH on a non-existent feature id. Source: US-1.
- **FR-006**: The system SHALL update `updated_at` on every successful PATCH and return the updated `FeatureDetail` JSON with `200 OK`. Source: US-1.
- **FR-007**: The system SHALL treat the `id` field as immutable; a body `id` differing from the path `id` is ignored. Source: US-1, human answer "ID stays immutable".
- **FR-008**: The system SHALL expose `DELETE /api/features/{id}` to hard-delete a feature. Source: US-2.
- **FR-009**: The system SHALL allow DELETE only when the feature status is `draft`, `done`, or `cancelled`; all other statuses return `409 Conflict` (`feature_not_deletable`). Source: US-2, human answer "Only draft or terminal features; in-progress must be cancelled first".
- **FR-010**: The system SHALL hard-delete: remove the feature row AND cascade-delete all related rows (questions, notes, events, gate_history, recirculations, sessions, and any other table with a `feature_id` FK). Source: US-2, human answer "Hard delete ‚Äî remove the feature row and cascade-delete related data".
- **FR-011**: The system SHALL return `204 No Content` on successful DELETE with an empty body. Source: US-2.
- **FR-012**: The system SHALL return `404 Not Found` (`feature_not_found`) for DELETE on a non-existent feature id. Source: US-2.
- **FR-013**: The system SHALL return `400 Bad Request` (`validation_error`, "Invalid JSON body") for malformed JSON on PATCH. Source: US-1.
- **FR-014**: The system SHALL enforce a 1MB request body cap on PATCH (via `http.MaxBytesReader`). Source: US-1 (consistency with create).
- **FR-015**: The system SHALL clean up the spec worktree directory and `spec/{id}` git branch on hard delete, best-effort (missing worktree/branch must not fail the request). Source: US-2 edge case.
- **FR-016**: The UI SHALL show an edit affordance on the feature detail page that opens a form with title and priority fields pre-filled. Source: US-1, human answer "Feature detail page only ‚Äî an edit affordance opens an edit form there".
- **FR-017**: The UI SHALL show a Delete button on the feature detail page only when the feature is in a deletable state (`draft`/`done`/`cancelled`); non-deletable states show a disabled button with a tooltip. Source: US-2, human answers.
- **FR-018**: The UI SHALL show a confirm dialog before issuing DELETE. Source: US-2, human answer "Delete button on the feature detail page behind a confirm dialog".
- **FR-019**: The UI SHALL navigate away from the detail page (back to the dashboard) after a successful delete. Source: US-2.
- **FR-020**: The dashboard list SHALL reflect edits and deletions without requiring a hard refresh when the user returns to it. Source: US-3.
- **FR-021**: `GET /api/features` SHALL continue to return `200 OK` with `features: []` (never `null`, never `404`) when no features exist. Source: US-3 edge case (preserve existing behavior).
### Key Entities
## Success Criteria
- **SC-001**: A user can change a draft feature's title and priority via the detail page UI and see the new values persisted (round-trip verified by `GET`).
- **SC-002**: A user can delete a draft or terminal feature via the detail page UI behind a confirm dialog; the feature and all its related rows are removed from the database.
- **SC-003**: `PATCH`/`DELETE` on an in-progress or waiting-for-feedback feature returns `409 Conflict` (no partial mutation).
- **SC-004**: `GET /api/features` returns `200 OK` with `features: []` when the database is empty (regression-preserved).
- **SC-005**: After a delete, the deleted feature's `feature_id` appears in zero rows across `questions`, `notes`, `events`, `gate_history`, `recirculations`, `sessions` (verifiable by SQL count query).
- **SC-006**: The dashboard list reflects edits and deletions on the next fetch without a browser hard refresh.
- **SC-007**: All new endpoints return the documented HTTP status codes (200/204/400/404/409) for the documented inputs ‚Äî verified by integration tests covering each code.
## Assumptions
