# Spec: crud-feature

Feature ID: crud-feature
Phase: inception
Author: pm

---

## Workspace Summary (Brownfield)

This feature is added to the **Dev Team platform itself** ‚Äî an AI-DLC orchestrator written in Go (backend) with a React/TypeScript frontend.

- **Repo**: `devteam` (self-hosted platform). Worktree: `/home/lobsterdog/worktrees/devteam-specs/crud-feature` on branch `spec/crud-feature`.
- **Backend**: Go 1.x, stdlib `net/http` with Go 1.22 `mux.HandleFunc("METHOD /path", ...)` pattern routing. SQLite (default) or PostgreSQL via `database:` config in `devteam.yaml`. Migrations versioned in `internal/db/migration_NNN.go`, registered via `RegisterMigration`, run in transaction on startup, adapted for both SQLite+Postgres.
- **Frontend**: React + TypeScript + Vite. Components in `ui/src/components/`, pages in `ui/src/pages/` (`Dashboard.tsx`, `FeatureDetail.tsx`). API client in `ui/src/api/client.ts`. E2E: Playwright (`ui/e2e/`, port 18765).
- **Existing feature model** (`internal/feature/feature.go`):
  - `Feature` struct: `ID` (immutable slug), `Title`, `Current Phase`, `Status`, `Priority` (int 1-3), `IntakePath`, `SpecDir`, `CreatedAt`, `UpdatedAt`, `Dependencies`, `Repos`, `PreparedRepos`, `PhaseStates`.
  - Status enum: `draft, in_progress, gate_blocked, passed, failed, done, recirculated, cancelled, waiting_for_feedback`.
  - Phase enum: `inception, planning, construction, review, testing, delivery`.
  - Methods: `NewFeature`, `Start`, `AdvanceTo`, `RecirculateTo`, `Cancel`, `MarkDone`, `IsTerminal`, `Slug`.
  - `Priority` validated by `IsValidPriority` (1-3).
- **Existing API** (`internal/api/server.go`):
  - `GET /api/features` ‚Üí `listFeatures` (returns `{"features":[...], "total_count":N}`)
  - `POST /api/features` ‚Üí `createFeature` (validates title 1-200 chars, description non-empty, priority 1-3 defaulting 2; type `loose_idea|external_spec`)
  - `GET /api/features/{id}` ‚Üí `getFeature`
  - `POST /api/features/{id}/cancel` ‚Üí `cancelFeature`
  - `POST /api/features/{id}/recirculate` ‚Üí `recirculateFeature`
  - No PATCH/PUT/DELETE for feature metadata. No edit endpoint. No delete endpoint.
- **Existing UI**: `FeatureDetail.tsx` renders a feature; `FeatureCard.tsx`/`FeatureList.tsx` for the dashboard. Cancel/recirculate actions exist. No edit form, no delete button.
- **Conventions to follow**:
  - Error responses use `writeError(w, status, code, message)` with `{error, details}` shape (see `ErrorResponse` DTO). Codes are snake_case strings (`empty_title`, `title_too_long`, `invalid_priority`, `feature_not_found`, `internal_error`, `validation_error`).
  - Success responses use `writeJSON(w, status, payload)`.
  - Request body size capped via `http.MaxBytesReader(w, r.Body, 1<<20)` (1 MiB).
  - JSON arrays initialized to `[]` not `null` (e.g. `FeaturesToSummaryResponse` uses `make([]..., 0, len(...))`).
  - DB writes guarded by `if s.db != nil`.
  - Feature rows in `features` table; questions/notes/etc. have FK to `features.id`. Cascade-delete must remove related rows (questions, notes, gate_history, sessions, recirculations, events, spec_artifacts).
  - Phase routing uses Go 1.22 `"METHOD /path"` string pattern; `{id}` path values via `r.PathValue("id")`.
  - No constitution.md present ‚Äî no project-level principles to gate against.

---

## Constraint Register

No external RFC/standard governs a CRUD feature on an internal platform. Constraints are derived from the existing codebase conventions (the de-facto standard for this repo). Each constraint references its source location.

| ID | Source | Section/Vector | Type | Constraint | Verification Method |
|----|--------|----------------|------|------------|---------------------|
| CON-001 | server.go:279 | createFeature | consistency | Error code style is snake_case strings; edit/delete endpoints must use existing codes (`validation_error`, `feature_not_found`, `internal_error`) and introduce new ones in the same style | API test asserting error codes |
| CON-002 | server.go:275 | createFeature | consistency | Request bodies capped at 1 MiB via `http.MaxBytesReader`; edit endpoint must do the same | Oversized-body test |
| CON-003 | dto.go | ErrorResponse | consistency | Error response shape is `{"error":<code>,"details":<msg>}`; new endpoints must match | Response shape assertion |
| CON-004 | dto.go:92-108 | FeaturesToSummaryResponse | correctness | JSON arrays are `[]` not `null`; edit response DTOs must follow | Serialization test |
| CON-005 | feature.go:190-192 | IsValidPriority | correctness | Priority must be integer 1, 2, or 3; edit endpoint must reject out-of-range with `invalid_priority` | Out-of-range priority test |
| CON-006 | server.go:283-290 | createFeature | correctness | Title must be non-empty trimmed and ‚â§200 chars; edit endpoint must enforce the same with codes `empty_title`/`title_too_long` | Empty/oversized title test |
| CON-007 | human answer | edit fields | scope | Only `title` and `priority` are editable on an existing feature; `id` is immutable | Attempt to edit id field test |
| CON-008 | human answer | edit id | scope | Feature ID is immutable across all edits | Mutation test |
| CON-009 | human answer | edit restrictions | correctness | No edits while feature status is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`; user must wait for completion or cancel first | Edit-while-processing test (expect 409) |
| CON-010 | human answer | edit affordance | scope | Editing is available from the feature detail page only, via an edit affordance that opens an edit form there; no inline edit in the list | UI e2e test |
| CON-011 | human answer | delete trigger | scope | Delete is a button on the feature detail page behind a confirm dialog | UI e2e test |
| CON-012 | human answer | deletable states | correctness | Only `draft` or terminal (`done`/`cancelled`) features may be deleted; `in_progress` features must be cancelled first (expect 409) | Delete-while-in-progress test |
| CON-013 | human answer | delete semantics | correctness | Delete is hard: remove the feature row AND cascade-delete all related data | DB row-count + cascade assertion |
| CON-014 | AGENTS.md | migrations | consistency | Schema changes go in `internal/db/migration_NNN.go`, registered via `RegisterMigration`, transactional, adapted for SQLite+Postgres | Migration file inspection |
| CON-015 | server.go:184 | routing | consistency | New routes use Go 1.22 `"METHOD /path"` pattern with `{id}` path values via `r.PathValue` | Route registration inspection |

---

## User Stories

### US-001: Rename / reprioritize a feature
**Story**: As a product manager, I can edit the title and priority of an existing feature from the feature detail page so that the feature record stays accurate as understanding evolves.
**Priority**: P1
**Why this priority**: Core CRUD primitive; without it, the feature record is write-once, forcing cancellation+recreation to fix a typo. This is the MVP ‚Äî implementing it alone yields a usable product.
**Independent test**: Create a feature, open its detail page, click edit, change title+priority, save, assert the detail page and list reflect the new values.

### US-002: Delete a feature
**Story**: As a product manager, I can delete a draft or terminal feature from the feature detail page so that obsolete or mistakenly-created features are removed from the system.
**Priority**: P1
**Why this priority**: Core CRUD primitive; hard-delete with cascade is the second half of CRUD. Without it, the system accumulates dead records forever.
**Independent test**: Create a feature, open its detail page, click delete, confirm, assert it no longer appears in the list and its related rows (questions, notes) are gone.

### US-003: Block edits while processing
**Story**: As a product manager, I cannot edit a feature that is currently being processed by the pipeline so that in-flight state is not corrupted.
**Priority**: P1
**Why this priority**: Data-safety guard. Without it, edits race the pipeline and corrupt phase state.
**Independent test**: Set a feature to `in_progress`, attempt an edit, assert a 409 with a clear error code.

### US-004: Block delete of in-progress features
**Story**: As a product manager, I cannot delete a feature that is in progress; I must cancel it first so that running pipeline work is not orphaned.
**Priority**: P1
**Why this priority**: Data-safety guard. Without it, deletes orphan running agents and leave dangling worktrees.
**Independent test**: Set a feature to `in_progress`, attempt a delete, assert a 409 with a clear error code.

---

## Functional Requirements

- **FR-001**: The system shall expose `PATCH /api/features/{id}` accepting a JSON body with optional `title` (string, 1-200 chars trimmed) and `priority` (int 1-3). Source: US-001.
- **FR-002**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall reject a request that changes the feature `id` with `400 validation_error` ("id is immutable"). Source: CON-007, CON-008, US-001.
- **FR-003**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall validate title with the same rules as create: non-empty trimmed (`400 empty_title`), ‚â§200 chars (`400 title_too_long`). Source: CON-006, US-001.
- **FR-004**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall validate priority is 1, 2, or 3, returning `400 invalid_priority` otherwise. Source: CON-005, US-001.
- **FR-005**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall return `409 feature_in_progress` when the feature status is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`. Source: CON-009, US-003.
- **FR-006**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall return `404 feature_not_found` when the id does not exist. Source: CON-001, US-001.
- **FR-007**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` on success shall return `200` with the full `FeatureDetailResponse` (matching `GET /api/features/{id}` shape), reflecting the updated title/priority and a refreshed `updated_at`. Source: CON-004, US-001.
- **FR-008**: `PATCH /api/features/{id}` shall cap the request body at 1 MiB via `http.MaxBytesReader`. Source: CON-002, US-001.
- **FR-009**: The system shall expose `DELETE /api/features/{id}`. Source: US-002.
- **FR-010**: `DELETE /api/features/{id}` shall return `409 feature_in_progress` when the feature status is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`. Source: CON-012, US-004.
- **FR-011**: `DELETE /api/features/{id}` shall return `404 feature_not_found` when the id does not exist. Source: CON-001, US-002.
- **FR-012**: `DELETE /api/features/{id}` on success shall hard-delete the feature row and cascade-delete all related data (questions, notes, gate_history, sessions, recirculations, events, spec_artifacts) and return `204` with no body. Source: CON-013, US-002.
- **FR-013**: The cascade-delete shall be implemented as a versioned migration (`internal/db/migration_NNN.go`) declaring `ON DELETE CASCADE` foreign keys (or equivalent transactional delete for the tables not under FK), registered via `RegisterMigration`, transactional, adapted for both SQLite and PostgreSQL. Source: CON-014, US-002.
- **FR-014**: The UI feature detail page (`ui/src/pages/FeatureDetail.tsx`) shall show an edit affordance that opens an edit form with title and priority fields, pre-filled with current values, and a save action that calls `PATCH /api/features/{id}`. Source: CON-010, US-001.
- **FR-015**: The UI feature detail page shall show a delete button behind a confirm dialog; confirming calls `DELETE /api/features/{id}` and, on success, navigates to the dashboard. Source: CON-011, US-002.
- **FR-016**: The UI shall disable/hide the edit affordance and delete button when the feature status is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`. Source: CON-009, CON-012, US-003, US-004.
- **FR-017**: The API client (`ui/src/api/client.ts`) shall expose `updateFeature(id, {title?, priority?})` and `deleteFeature(id)` functions. Source: US-001, US-002.

---

## Key Entities

### Feature (extended behavior, no new fields)
- Existing `Feature` struct in `internal/feature/feature.go`. No new attributes required.
- Editable fields: `Title` (string 1-200), `Priority` (int 1-3).
- Immutable fields: `ID`, `CreatedAt`, `IntakePath`, `SpecDir`, `PhaseStates` (pipeline-owned).
- New methods to add:
  - `func (f *Feature) Edit(title string, priority int) error` ‚Äî validates and applies title+priority, refreshes `UpdatedAt`. Returns error on invalid input. Rejects (no-op + error) when `f.Status` is `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback`.

### State transitions (no change to existing machine)
- Existing phase machine: `inception ‚Üí planning ‚Üí construction ‚Üí review ‚Üí testing ‚Üí delivery`.
- Existing status machine: `draft ‚Üí in_progress ‚Üí (gate_blocked|passed|failed|recirculated|waiting_for_feedback) ‚Üí done|cancelled`.
- **New transitions**: none. Edit and delete are side-effects on the record, not phase transitions. Edit is only allowed from `draft` or any status where the pipeline is not actively processing (`in_progress`, `waiting_for_feedback` excluded). Delete is only allowed from `draft`, `done`, or `cancelled`.

---

## Acceptance Scenarios (Given/When/Then)

See `acceptance.md` for the full enumerated criteria per story.

Summary of error/empty-state behavior:

| User Action | Success | Error Condition | Expected Response |
|---|---|---|---|
| Edit feature (PATCH) | 200 with updated `FeatureDetailResponse` | Missing/empty title | 400 `empty_title` |
| Edit feature | 200 | Title > 200 chars | 400 `title_too_long` |
| Edit feature | 200 | Priority not 1/2/3 | 400 `invalid_priority` |
| Edit feature | 200 | Attempt to change `id` | 400 `validation_error` ("id is immutable") |
| Edit feature | 200 | Feature not found | 404 `feature_not_found` |
| Edit feature | 200 | Feature `in_progress`/`waiting_for_feedback` | 409 `feature_in_progress` |
| Edit feature | 200 | Body > 1 MiB | 400 (MaxBytesReader) |
| Edit feature | 200 | Malformed JSON | 400 `validation_error` |
| Delete feature (DELETE) | 204 no body | Feature not found | 404 `feature_not_found` |
| Delete feature | 204 | Feature `in_progress`/`waiting_for_feedback` | 409 `feature_in_progress` |
| List features (existing) | 200 `{"features":[], "total_count":0}` | No features | 200 with empty array (not 404, not null) |

---

## Success Criteria

- **SC-001**: A user can change a feature's title and priority via the UI edit form and see the change persisted on reload (verified by re-fetching `GET /api/features/{id}` and asserting the new values).
- **SC-002**: A user can delete a draft or terminal feature via the UI delete button + confirm dialog, and the feature no longer appears in `GET /api/features`.
- **SC-003**: After a hard delete, no rows referencing the deleted feature id remain in `questions`, `notes`, `gate_history`, `sessions`, `recirculations`, `events`, or `spec_artifacts` (verified by direct DB query).
- **SC-004**: `PATCH` and `DELETE` on a feature with status `in_progress` or `waiting_for_feedback` return `409` and leave the feature unchanged (verified by re-fetching and asserting unchanged `title`, `priority`, `status`).
- **SC-005**: `PATCH` and `DELETE` on a non-existent id return `404 feature_not_found`.
- **SC-006**: All new error codes are snake_case and the response shape matches `{"error":<code>,"details":<msg>}` (verified by inspecting every new error path).
- **SC-007**: JSON responses never return `null` for array fields (verified by checking `features`, `dependencies`, `repos`, `artifacts`, `checks` are `[]` when empty).

---

## Assumptions

- **[ASSUMPTION: single-tenant]** The platform is single-user/local; no row-level authorization (RBAC) is required on edit/delete. The existing endpoints have no auth, so new endpoints follow suit. The security extension's threat model is noted but P1 auth is out of scope for this feature.
- **[ASSUMPTION: optimistic UI]** No optimistic concurrency token (`If-Match`/ETag) is required; the `409 feature_in_progress` guard is sufficient to prevent the dangerous race (edit-during-processing). Concurrent edits by two users may last-writer-win; acceptable for a local tool.
- **[ASSUMPTION: cascade via FK]** The cascade-delete is implemented by adding `ON DELETE CASCADE` to existing foreign keys in a migration, plus explicit `DELETE FROM` statements for any tables not under FK. The migration runs in a transaction and is adapted for SQLite (FKs must be enabled, which they are by default in modern SQLite via `PRAGMA foreign_keys=ON`) and PostgreSQL.
- **[ASSUMPTION: no audit trail for edits]** Edit history is not recorded; only `updated_at` is bumped. A future `events` row could capture edits but is out of scope.
- **[ASSUMPTION: no soft-delete]** Delete is hard, per human answer. No `deleted_at` column.
- **[ASSUMPTION: edit/delete while `gate_blocked`/`passed`/`failed`/`recirculated` is allowed]** These statuses indicate the pipeline is not actively running an agent; the `in_progress` and `waiting_for_feedback` exclusions are the precise guard. (Human answer said "in-progress must be cancelled first"; `gate_blocked`/`passed`/`failed`/`recirculated` are not "in-progress" pipeline runs.)

---

## Out of Scope

- Bulk edit / bulk delete.
- Inline edit from the feature list (explicitly rejected by human answer ‚Äî detail page only).
- Editing fields other than `title` and `priority` (description, intake_path, repos, dependencies ‚Äî all immutable post-creation).
- Editing the feature `id`.
- Soft delete / trash / undo.
- Audit log of edits.
- Row-level authorization / RBAC.
- Pagination/filtering/sorting of the feature list (existing behavior unchanged).

---

## Constitution Compliance

No `constitution.md` exists in the repo root or `.specify/constitution.md`. No project-level principles gate this spec. N/A.

---

## Open Questions for Architect

None. All ambiguities resolved via human answers. The architect should confirm the cascade-delete migration approach against the actual schema in `internal/db/` (the PM has not read every migration file; the architect must verify which tables reference `features.id` and whether FKs already exist or need adding).
